rao. Adulescens] i. e. ‘young man,' is constantly employed by dramatists in addressing and describing a person without reference, at least emphatically, to his age. It is not employed when one person accosts another ceremoniously, and occasionally, although by no means uniformly, implies that the person addressed is in a social position somewhat inferior to that of the speaker. It may thus be often correctly represented by our phrase ‘my lad,' ‘my man,’ or ‘my friend! In like manner puer is the common term applied to a slave, whatever his age may be; so in French a walter is called garcon although he may be old and decrepit‚ and among ourselves the same takes place with regard to post-boys.
